(1, '2012-05-31 00:00:00', '2012-11-20 22:21:01', 2, 'Content Management System (CMS) in PHP', '<p>This is the first article posted in my new PHP content management system. It was thrown together quickly and is still missing quite a bit, but it''s a good start using PHP, MySQL, HTML5, CSS3, & Javascript. Information gathered to build my CMS came from articles at the following sites:\r\n<br/>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.elated.com">http://www.elated.com</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://css-tricks.com">http://css-tricks.com</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://net.tutsplus.com">http://net.tutsplus.com</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</p>', 'News, PHP, SQL, CSS, HTML5, Javascript', ''),
(2, '2012-08-13 00:00:00', '2012-11-20 22:21:13', 2, 'What''s next?', '<p>Now that I''ve got the basic CMS framework up, running, and hosted online; it''s time to fine tune features and add some details. (The site is currently pretty thin) So here is the current list of things I would like to add.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><del>Pagination on the article archive (front end) and article list (back end) so that the system can easily handle hundreds of articles</del></li>\r\n<li><del>Admin preview capability, so the admin can see how an article will look before publishing it</del></li>\r\n<li><del>Article categories or tags</del></li>\r\n<li><del>Facebook API Login, Like button, Comments</del></li>\r\n<li>Search by tags</li>\r\n<li>Apache''s mod_rewrite permalinks</li>\r\n<li>Content</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</p>', 'News, Updates', ''),
